Effects are cached in a private static field in `Effect.EffectCache`. But the only code that calls the internal `Effect.FlushCache()` is `Game.Dispose()`.

It took me a while to figure out that this is the root cause of why some of my visual tests are failing. I'm not using a `Game` object - I'm just creating lower-level objects like `GraphicsDevice` directly. But because I'm disposing the `GraphicsDevice` and other graphics resources after each test, any effects left in the cache are unusable. Any subsequent tests that use the same `Effect` don't work.

I'm not sure what the best solution is - it seems like cached effects should be removed when the `GraphicsDevice` used to create them (rather than the `Game`) is disposed? Or at least, when the `Effect` itself is disposed (I think `GraphicsDevice.Dispose` already calls `Dispose` on `GraphicsResource` objects, so that may be enough).

For now, I've worked around it with this, but it's not pretty:

``` csharp
typeof(Effect).GetMethod("FlushCache", BindingFlags.NonPublic | BindingFlags.Static).Invoke(null, null);
```

**EDIT**: I've just run into a similar issue with state objects - I get exceptions because they are associated with a different graphics device. Basically, I think I need to be able to [what Game is doing here](https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/blob/develop/MonoGame.Framework/Game.cs#L120) (or even better, have it happen implicitly when `GraphicsDevice` is disposed):

``` csharp
if (_graphicsDeviceManager != null)
{
    Effect.FlushCache();
    BlendState.ResetStates();
    DepthStencilState.ResetStates();
    RasterizerState.ResetStates();
    SamplerState.ResetStates();

    ...
}
```

Xamarin's decision to omit the MonoTouch (or anything else) from the namespaces
in the new API makes it rather inconvenient to use classes that have the same name as
Xamarin's namespaces. One such example is MediaPlayer.

You will get an error like this:

> Error CS0234: The type or namespace name `Play' does not exist in the
> namespace`MediaPlayer'. Are you missing an assembly reference?

That's because the compiler will see `MediaPlayer` as a namespace name instead of MonoGame's class.

Using a namespace alias outside your namespace declaration won't work either:

> using MediaPlayer = Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Media.MediaPlayer;
> Error CS0576: Namespace `global::' contains a definition with same name as
> alias`MediaPlayer'

However, declaring it inside your namespace will work:

``` C#
// Not here

namespace MyGame
{
    // But here
    using MediaPlayer = Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Media.MediaPlayer;

    public class MyClass { }
}
```

Due to the very general names in the iOS SDK you will expect similar behavior with other class names like Accounts, Dialog, Photos, Social and Security.
